<h2>The Question</h2>
<p>
  <a href="/backlog/232-component-compiler-deferred-strategy-optins/">#232</a> collects the
  <code>&lt;component&gt;</code> compiler opt-ins deferred out of
  <a href="/backlog/231-component-compiler-strategy-axes/">#231</a> (which shipped the top-2-per-axis
  baseline of <a href="/backlog/127-component-compiler-toolchain-reach/">#127</a>'s
  "configurable strategy axes, native-first defaults" ruling — the
  <em>component-dc</em> decision cluster). It was re-typed <code>decision → epic</code> on 2026-06-22
  with the claim "no merit fork here — support-all, not branches of a fork" — but that claim was
  <strong>asserted, never grounded in a prior-art survey</strong>. This research supplies the missing
  grounding: is any of the deferred opt-ins actually a fork (mutually exclusive with a sibling, or a
  forced invariant with a broken alternative), or are they all additive, support-all opt-ins on
  orthogonal axes?
</p>
<p>The concerns under test:</p>
