<h2>What the survey found</h2>

<h3>A · SFC dedicated-file surfaces are additive, never forced</h3>
<p>
  Every SFC ecosystem treats the dedicated extension as one coexisting compile surface, not a
  replacement: <a href="https://vuejs.org/guide/scaling-up/sfc.html">Vue documents SFCs as
  optional</a> beside plain-JS objects, inline templates, and render functions ("Vue can still be
  used via plain JavaScript without a build step");
  <a href="https://docs.astro.build/en/basics/astro-components/">Astro</a> renders
  <code>.astro</code> files alongside React/Vue/Svelte island components; Svelte's
  <code>.svelte</code> is a compiler input surface over the same component model. A dedicated file
  extension is exactly the shape of an <em>additive</em> source-surface opt-in.
</p>

<h3>B · SWC WASM plugins cannot reuse a JS kernel — a cost, not a fork</h3>
<p>
  An <a href="https://swc.rs/docs/plugin/ecmascript/getting-started">SWC ecmascript plugin</a> runs
  inside SWC's Rust pipeline as a Rust <code>VisitMut</code> over the SWC AST (the host serializes
  the AST into the WASM runtime and back). So a <code>&lt;component&gt;</code> SWC plugin must
  <strong>re-implement the lowering in Rust</strong> — it cannot wrap the shared JS
  <code>compile()</code> kernel the bundler wrappers and the <code>tsc</code> transformer reuse. It
  also carries a real ABI tax: plugins were historically pinned to <code>swc_core</code> versions
  (<a href="https://swc.rs/docs/plugin/ecmascript/compatibility">compatibility table</a>), eased
  post-<code>@swc/core</code> v1.15.0
  (<a href="https://blog.swc.rs/2025-11-4-wasm-backward-compatibility">CBOR + <code>Unknown</code>
  enum arms</a>) but only for plugins on <code>swc_core ≥ 47</code> — and
  <a href="https://nextjs.org/docs/architecture/nextjs-compiler">Next/Turbopack</a> SWC-plugin
  integration remains rough. <strong>None of this is mutual exclusion</strong> — enabling the SWC
  path excludes nothing; it duplicates the kernel's behaviour at a deeper integration point. It is a
  cost/maturity finding that independently validates #1629's <code>maturityGated</code> parking
  (building it now, with no heavy-SWC consumer to prove byte-identity against, yields a worse
  artifact).
</p>

<h3>C · Vanilla <code>tsc</code> has no transformer hook; <code>ts-patch</code> is the maintained filler</h3>
<p>
  TypeScript's transformer API is programmatic-only: the <code>tsconfig</code> <code>plugins</code>
  array feeds only the language service, and the official transformer-plugin proposal
  (<a href="https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/54276">microsoft/TypeScript#54276</a>) is
  unshipped. The gap #1630 fills is real and only third-party-fillable.
  <strong>Delta:</strong> <a href="https://github.com/cevek/ttypescript">ttypescript is
  deprecated</a> (TS &lt; 5 only); <a href="https://github.com/nonara/ts-patch">ts-patch</a> is the
  maintained successor and performs real emit-time source lowering — and the shipped FUI transformer
  re-wraps the same shared <code>compile()</code> core, no kernel re-implementation.
</p>

<h3>D · The three axes are independent, stacked knobs in shipping ecosystems</h3>
<p>
  Vue runs the analogous three simultaneously:
  <code>.vue</code> files (source surface) +
  <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/@vitejs/plugin-vue"><code>@vitejs/plugin-vue</code></a>/unplugin
  integrations (toolchain depth) +
  <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/vue-tsc"><code>vue-tsc</code></a>
  (<code>tsc</code>-side support) — see the
  <a href="https://vuejs.org/guide/scaling-up/tooling.html">Vue tooling guide</a>. "Which extension I
  author in", "which toolchain depth I integrate at", and "do I support a bundler-less
  <code>tsc</code>-only pipeline" are independent, composable knobs — never exclusive.
</p>

<h2>Verdict</h2>
<p>
  <strong>Composability probe: PASS. No fork exists among the three carved opt-ins.</strong> Each of
  the three surveyed opt-ins is a support-all, additive opt-in on an orthogonal strategy axis of the
  #127 contract; no pair is mutually exclusive and no alternative is broken. (The fourth,
  <em>uncarved</em> arbitrary-string-scanning residual was <strong>not probed</strong> by this survey
  — its child re-runs the standing test at carve time and may legitimately be a real decision on
  match-rule correctness.) The only residue the survey surfaced is
  <em>cost/sequencing</em> on the SWC path (Rust re-implementation + ABI upkeep) — a prioritization
  input the <em>not-a-prioritization</em> rule keeps out of any fork, already correctly encoded as
  #1629's <code>maturityGated</code> un-gate trigger. #232 therefore stays <code>kind: epic</code>
  in support-all shape (zero <code>## Fork N</code>), with the ts-patch deprecation delta and the
  uncarved arbitrary-string-scanning residual folded into its body. Full session grounding in the
  linked report.
</p>
